Sprague Project The Sprague Project site is located in Bates County approximately six miles west of State Highway 71 at Rich Hill, Mo.
Missouri AML chose this location because an eroding highwall threatened the public safety along Highway A and wetlands could be constructed on land owned and managed by the Missouri Department of Conservation within the Peabody Conservation Area.
Construction was completed in spring 1998.
A dangerous mining highwall along Highway A was backfilled and an access road with limited highway visibility was moved to protect public safety.
The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers delineated approximately 1.6 acres of wetlands within the proposed project area.
As a result, a total of 8.8 acres of wetlands were constructed to mitigate losses at both the Sprague and Bison projects.
Water levels within the wetland can be manipulated by wildlife managers to maximize benefits to wildlife.
An additional 18-acres of abandoned mine lands were reclaimed at the Sprague project.
Seeding was completed in spring 1998.
